\section{Introduction}


The proper evaluation of averages in statistical physics
requires the recourse to the  Gibbs idealization of infinitely many copies of the same system, namely, to the Gibbs ensemble that is of fundamental importance for the theoretical predictions.
In practice, when only the observation of a single system is possible, this ideal ensemble average is assumed to be identical to the more accessible average in time on the same system. This is the ergodic assumption that 
the tracking of single molecules proves to be frequently violated \cite{review}, a phenomenon called \emph{ergodicity breaking}.  Establishing a good theoretical command of ergodicity breaking is of fundamental importance when we move from physics  to biology, to physiology and to sociology, since ergodicity breaking seems to be a general property of complex systems in the out of equilibrium condition. 

It has to be stressed, however, that one of the origins of the ergodicity breaking observed in molecular diffusion in biological cells, is the occurrence of non-Poisson renewal (NPR) events, which produces a form of
out of equilibrium condition that is not to be confused
with a more conventional form of out of equilibrium evolution such as the slow regression to thermodynamical equilibrium, and with another cause of non-renewal ergodicity breaking that we shall discuss hereby. In fact, a renewal event is equivalent to a total rejuvenation of the system, with no memory of the earlier events, and, in spite of this total independence of the earlier events, it gives the impression of being characterized by extended memory.
This is especially evident when  the time distance between the occurrence of two consecutive renewal events is described by a waiting time distribution with a diverging first moment. In this case we may find a condition where the random walker has just occupied the same position $x$ for a large time in the past,  leading us to make the plausible conjecture that it will keep that position in the future, the future inactivity being a sort of memory of the past inactivity. 
